WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.880
[Amit Varma]: While planning this episode of the scene in the unseen, I was filled with gratitude at

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:14.800
[Amit Varma]: one point, gratitude for my independence. No one tells me who to call on my show or

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:19.280
[Amit Varma]: what to discuss. As far as the content of the show is concerned, I'm a one man team.

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:22.640
[Amit Varma]: As far as the production of it is concerned, I had teamed up with a podcast production

00:00:22.640 --> 00:00:27.280
[Amit Varma]: house for a while. But now I produce the show myself. I've contracted with my editor Vijay

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:33.040
[Amit Varma]: Doifode and my illustrator Alika Gupta. And while we work together, I make all the decisions.

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:37.880
[Amit Varma]: No mybop interferes from on top. And I have no difficulty distributing the show and getting

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:42.760
[Amit Varma]: to such a vast audience. It would not be like this if I worked for a mainstream media house

00:00:42.760 --> 00:00:46.960
[Amit Varma]: today, even if I would have made much more money working for one. I thought of this while

00:00:46.960 --> 00:00:52.680
[Amit Varma]: reading the excellent book, Twitter and tear gas by Zeynep Tufekci, where she quoted a

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:57.360
[Amit Varma]: journalist in Turkey, who once said the following words to her, which frankly could be said

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:04.200
[Amit Varma]: in India in 2020. The unnamed journalist said, quote, I first censor myself, as I know I'll

00:01:04.200 --> 00:01:08.280
[Amit Varma]: be in trouble if I write something critical of the government. And then my editor censors

00:01:08.280 --> 00:01:12.560
[Amit Varma]: me if I haven't been mild enough. And then owners of the newspaper also check to make

00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:17.040
[Amit Varma]: sure nothing too critical gets through. And if something is published anyway, especially

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:22.280
[Amit Varma]: if in defiance, someone from the government calls our boss, and then the tax inspectors

00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:27.520
[Amit Varma]: are sent in to find something to find the newspapers with. Stop good. This quote is

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:32.040
[Amit Varma]: from Turkey. And this kind of clampdown of the media ensures that the media can often

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:36.880
[Amit Varma]: be a propaganda machine. Take the problem of the Kurds. For example, the Turkish people

00:01:36.880 --> 00:01:42.400
[Amit Varma]: were constantly brainwashed with misinformation about the Kurds. For example, Tufekci writes,

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:47.800
[Amit Varma]: quote, during the military regime of the 1980s, the Kurds were referred to in the mass media

00:01:47.800 --> 00:01:52.760
[Amit Varma]: as mountain Turks, Turks who were a little misguided about the ethnicity and language,

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:57.760
[Amit Varma]: rather than an actual minority. This was of course ridiculous. Turkish and Kurdish don't

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:03.460
[Amit Varma]: even belong to the same language family. But in the censored military regime, such outlandish

00:02:03.460 --> 00:02:09.560
[Amit Varma]: claims could be made with a straight face. Stop good. A few years later, something happened

00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:14.680
[Amit Varma]: that could be considered a routine incident. Turkish military jets flew near the Iraq border

00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:20.360
[Amit Varma]: and bombed and killed 34 Kurdish smugglers. Smuggling was routine, the authorities knew

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:24.880
[Amit Varma]: about it. And at worst, you'd arrest smugglers and give them a shakedown, not bomb them with

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:30.560
[Amit Varma]: military jets. Anyway, the Turkish military then spun the incident. And all that was reported

00:02:30.560 --> 00:02:35.840
[Amit Varma]: in the news was that a few terrorists had been killed at the border. Reporters and managers

00:02:35.840 --> 00:02:40.680
[Amit Varma]: at mainstream media outlets were uneasy. They knew something was off, but they couldn't

00:02:40.680 --> 00:02:45.760
[Amit Varma]: report it. Then one reporter, Sardar Akinan, working in a newsroom where his bosses had

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:50.400
[Amit Varma]: shut out the incident, took the initiative. He bought a plane ticket on his own dime,

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:54.640
[Amit Varma]: flew to the nearest airport, took a cab and went to the village, which was the center

00:02:54.640 --> 00:03:00.480
[Amit Varma]: of the action. As he entered the village, he spotted what Tufekci describes as quote,

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:07.440
[Amit Varma]: a snaking line of coffins coming down a small hill as families wailed all around. Stop good.

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:13.040
[Amit Varma]: The coffins passed him and went on and on. The wailing went on and on. Akinan broke down.

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:18.120
[Amit Varma]: In another day and age in the 1980s or the 1990s, this would have been the private grief

00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:23.960
[Amit Varma]: of a surprised outsider. But this was 2011. Akinan took out his smartphone and snapped

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:29.880
[Amit Varma]: a picture of the snaking coffins. He put it on Instagram. He put it on Twitter. And soon

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:38.760
[Unknown]: the whole world knew. Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics,

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:46.160
[Unknown]: politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma. Welcome to The Seen

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:52.080
[Amit Varma]: and the Unseen. My subject for today is radically networked societies. Once upon a time, there

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:57.160
[Amit Varma]: were constraints to how fast and how much information could get out. Constraints of

00:03:57.160 --> 00:04:02.240
[Amit Varma]: both technology and the coercive state. But today, thanks to the internet and smartphones

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:07.160
[Amit Varma]: and social media, we are radically networked. One of the consequences of this is what we

00:04:07.160 --> 00:04:12.340
[Amit Varma]: saw in the famous Arab Spring of almost a decade ago, with popular uprisings in country

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:17.680
[Amit Varma]: after country enabled by technology forming spontaneously from the bottom up instead of

00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:22.720
[Amit Varma]: directed from the top. Reading Tufekci's book Twitter and Tear Gas, I was struck by some

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:27.320
[Amit Varma]: of the parallels between those protests and the protests that have erupted in India over

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:32.060
[Amit Varma]: the last few weeks. My eyes almost popped out in fact when Tufekci wrote about how one

00:04:32.060 --> 00:04:36.640
[Amit Varma]: common element to many of these protests was that a library would spring up in the middle

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:43.280
[Amit Varma]: of it. And I thought of Shaheen Bagh. Democracy, it struck me, must surely be deeper in a radically

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:48.680
[Amit Varma]: networked society. But there are also challenges. One challenge is that there is a flip side

00:04:48.680 --> 00:04:53.920
[Amit Varma]: to this as well. And radical networking can also be used to spread misinformation, such

00:04:53.920 --> 00:04:59.440
[Amit Varma]: as rumours about outsiders kidnapping children that have led to so many lynchings in India.

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:05.400
[Amit Varma]: Also there is a question of whether the coercive power of the state, also enhanced by technology,

00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:11.440
[Amit Varma]: is still too strong to counter. From a philosophical perspective also, questions arise about how

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:16.280
[Amit Varma]: the state should deal with the ill effects of such radical networking. There has always

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:21.680
[Amit Varma]: been a trade-off between liberty and security. Is this a false binary? If not, how do we

00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:26.980
[Amit Varma]: traverse this new landscape? To discuss this, I've invited my friend Pranay Kutasane, one

00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:31.920
[Amit Varma]: of the smartest people I know in India, who I absolutely love discussing ideas with. Pranay

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:36.360
[Amit Varma]: works at the Takshashila Institution in Bengaluru, and he has not just thought deeply about the

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:41.280
[Amit Varma]: subject of this episode, he has also taught it. But before we get to our discussion, let's

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:48.760
[Amit Varma]: take a quick commercial break. If you're listening to the seen and the unseen, it means you like

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:53.400
[Amit Varma]: listening to audio and you're thirsty for knowledge. That being the case, I'd urge you

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:58.640
[Amit Varma]: to check out Storytel, the sponsors of this episode. Storytel is an audiobook platform

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:03.260
[Amit Varma]: that has a massive range of audiobooks from around the world. Their international collection

