00:53:33.440 --> 00:53:36.760
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene and the unseen. I'm chatting with Pranay Koteswani about radically

00:53:36.760 --> 00:53:41.720
[Amit Varma]: network societies. And one of the things I forgot to mention in the first half of the

00:53:41.720 --> 00:53:48.080
[Amit Varma]: show before the break was I wanted to ask Pranay specifically about the Hong Kong protest

00:53:48.080 --> 00:53:51.320
[Amit Varma]: because he's actually written and thought about it a fair bit. Go ahead.

00:53:51.320 --> 00:53:57.400
[Guest]: Yeah, so Hong Kong is actually an RNS which is still going on, okay, as even as we speak,

00:53:57.400 --> 00:54:01.760
[Guest]: and it's sustained over many, many months. So it's an interesting case study. I just

00:54:01.760 --> 00:54:07.480
[Guest]: wanted to bring out a few elements of how digital media has a role to play in those

00:54:07.480 --> 00:54:13.520
[Guest]: protests. Okay, so the overall phrase that I use for this is the Hong Kong movement has

00:54:13.520 --> 00:54:20.600
[Guest]: been about moving your information trail offline, while moving your decision making and narrative

00:54:20.600 --> 00:54:26.400
[Guest]: online. Okay, so that is how I put it together. So what does it mean? Okay, so moving your

00:54:26.400 --> 00:54:33.320
[Guest]: information trail offline. Now remember, everyone knows the surveillance power and authority

00:54:33.320 --> 00:54:38.600
[Guest]: of the Chinese state that they use, right? So that's why the Hong Kong protesters have

00:54:38.600 --> 00:54:44.040
[Guest]: been trying to move their information trail offline. So they use a lot of cash, they don't

00:54:44.040 --> 00:54:49.360
[Guest]: so they are actually intentionally moving off the internet on for some purposes, right?

00:54:49.360 --> 00:54:53.920
[Guest]: So using cash, not using ATMs, because then you will be able to track people, they are

00:54:53.920 --> 00:55:00.040
[Guest]: turning off FaceTime ID or touch ID on their phones, because they again feel that people

00:55:00.040 --> 00:55:07.920
[Guest]: might use it. In many times, they have been using airdrop and Bluetooth file sharing in

00:55:07.920 --> 00:55:11.800
[Guest]: protest venues instead of the internet, because again, they fear that they can be tracked.

00:55:11.800 --> 00:55:17.520
[Guest]: So that is interesting. The second part of it was to move decision making actually online.

00:55:17.520 --> 00:55:23.640
[Guest]: So just look at Desirvo's report in BBC that some of the groups on Telegram, etc, have

00:55:23.640 --> 00:55:30.400
[Guest]: around 70,000 active subscribers, okay? And that represents 1% of Hong Kong's entire population.

00:55:30.400 --> 00:55:35.280
[Guest]: It's quite significant, right? And they also have specific groups for specific purposes.

00:55:35.280 --> 00:55:40.600
[Guest]: So there are groups for taking decisions. So they did like an online referendum of sorts,

00:55:40.600 --> 00:55:45.560
[Guest]: right? So whether we should continue protest the next day or not, that was voted on some

00:55:45.560 --> 00:55:51.680
[Guest]: of these groups with large memberships, right? Also, there were other groups which were more

00:55:51.680 --> 00:55:56.280
[Guest]: purpose oriented. So there were groups for medics, groups for supplying food when these

00:55:56.280 --> 00:56:02.480
[Guest]: protests were happening. So you know, you see entire decision making and the organization

00:56:02.480 --> 00:56:08.400
[Guest]: of this protest also moving online, okay? And the tools used were Telegram, Signal,

00:56:08.400 --> 00:56:15.160
[Guest]: which they thought was less under control of the Chinese state. So this is very fascinating,

00:56:15.160 --> 00:56:22.520
[Guest]: right? So digital media enabling the construction and the continuance of a protest is seen in

00:56:22.520 --> 00:56:24.200
[Amit Varma]: Hong Kong quite clearly.

00:56:24.200 --> 00:56:28.600
[Amit Varma]: And this is really interesting, because I'm specifically interested by Hong Kong as you

00:56:28.600 --> 00:56:33.160
[Amit Varma]: know, because the technology and the ways of communication there are evolving so quickly

00:56:33.160 --> 00:56:37.360
[Amit Varma]: that in some cases to get away from the Chinese government, they have to do what one could

00:56:37.360 --> 00:56:42.280
[Amit Varma]: term radical denetworking, yeah, and just kind of get off the internet. And it also

00:56:42.280 --> 00:56:47.240
[Amit Varma]: reminds me of a time where, you know, it isn't as if, you know, a technology may be built

00:56:47.240 --> 00:56:53.940
[Amit Varma]: to share cute cat pictures. But within that, users themselves build features, which can

00:56:53.940 --> 00:56:58.760
[Amit Varma]: be used for radical networking, for example, the hashtag, right, the hashtag is really

00:56:58.760 --> 00:57:03.720
[Amit Varma]: something that users innovated with first, and then they became a thing. And now you

00:57:03.720 --> 00:57:10.240
[Amit Varma]: can identify trends by it, and so on and so forth. And this kind of a bit of that happening

00:57:10.240 --> 00:57:16.680
[Amit Varma]: in Hong Kong. And do you think India will also sort of over here as well, we'll go in

00:57:16.680 --> 00:57:21.840
[Amit Varma]: some of those directions as the imperatives to keep protests going get stronger?

00:57:21.840 --> 00:57:27.320
[Guest]: Yeah. So one interesting thing about the protests that are that have happened over the last

00:57:27.320 --> 00:57:31.200
[Guest]: years are they have been prolonged in many of the countries. Some protests have been

00:57:31.200 --> 00:57:36.720
[Guest]: going on for more than a year as well. So it might play out that way. But that depends

00:57:36.720 --> 00:57:41.680
[Guest]: on the other aspect that we are going to talk about how the state will react. Just one point

00:57:41.680 --> 00:57:45.800
[Guest]: here about the Hong Kong protests to talk about the weak points of this, you know, one

00:57:45.800 --> 00:57:52.360
[Guest]: thing, again, this BBC report, which excellently captured all this said that these groups which

00:57:52.360 --> 00:57:57.320
[Guest]: were used to do a referenda type of decision making. So a lot of people said that whenever

00:57:57.320 --> 00:58:02.200
[Guest]: there is a black and white decision to be made, these groups really work well. But when

00:58:02.200 --> 00:58:08.600
[Guest]: there is a nuanced position to take, then these groups don't work as well as they would,

00:58:08.600 --> 00:58:14.600
[Guest]: we would want them to write. So that is something which we'll experience in other protests also

00:58:14.600 --> 00:58:15.600
[Guest]: through these tools.

00:58:15.600 --> 00:58:20.480
[Amit Varma]: Exactly. So let's let's kind of talk about the state. But before we bring the state in,

00:58:20.480 --> 00:58:24.560
[Amit Varma]: let's also you know, we've been talking about all of these protests, and many of these are

00:58:24.560 --> 00:58:30.240
[Amit Varma]: liberal protests, which you and I are sympathetic towards. But let's also acknowledge that one

00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:34.680
[Amit Varma]: radical network societies can be value neutral, you can, you know, use the scalability of

00:58:34.680 --> 00:58:40.040
[Amit Varma]: the internet to actually organize pogroms or genocides or has in fact happened lynchings

00:58:40.040 --> 00:58:44.360
[Amit Varma]: and so on. And, you know, before Mohammed the clock was killed, for example, there were

00:58:44.360 --> 00:58:48.560
[Amit Varma]: photos on WhatsApp, which had these narratives about, you know, perpetually showing pictures

00:58:48.560 --> 00:58:53.320
[Amit Varma]: of meat in his fridge and all of that nonsense. And we've had a problem in India, which I

00:58:53.320 --> 00:58:57.680
[Amit Varma]: discussed at length with Pratik Sinha last year, when I did an episode on fake news with

00:58:57.680 --> 00:59:03.280
[Amit Varma]: him about this mysterious sort of these rumors, which keep propagating across WhatsApp with

00:59:03.280 --> 00:59:07.920
[Amit Varma]: details change from locality to locality about how outsiders are coming in and kidnapping

00:59:07.920 --> 00:59:13.720
[Amit Varma]: kids, which led to a lot of alarmist lynchings that you saw an outsider in a strange car

00:59:13.720 --> 00:59:18.840
[Amit Varma]: and you assume that he must be one of those kid kidnappers and leave aside the motive

00:59:18.840 --> 00:59:23.560
[Amit Varma]: behind such rumors being spread as irrelevant. But I think it's clear that in cases like

00:59:23.560 --> 00:59:29.720
[Amit Varma]: that, the state needs to sort of step in and do something. And this is probably a good

00:59:29.720 --> 00:59:34.720
[Amit Varma]: time to sort of examine the role of the state and its duty vis-a-vis citizens as well, which

00:59:34.720 --> 00:59:37.000
[Guest]: is something you discussed in your paper with Nitin.

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:43.480
[Guest]: Yeah. So, let's look at this. So, fundamentally, we are seeing a clash between hierarchically

00:59:43.480 --> 00:59:47.800
[Guest]: structured states and radically networked societies, right? So, this is a fundamental

00:59:47.800 --> 00:59:53.540
[Guest]: clash. The problem, as we discussed, is information flows in these network communities will all

00:59:53.540 --> 00:59:58.720
[Guest]: always be faster than the decision making cycle and information flows in the state where

00:59:58.720 --> 01:00:04.160
[Guest]: it has to go from bottom to up, decision gets made, gets filtered to bottom, right? That's

01:00:04.160 --> 01:00:05.800
[Amit Varma]: going to take a lot of time.

01:00:05.800 --> 01:00:10.400
[Amit Varma]: And I think the way you guys put it was that states are relics of the industrial age and

01:00:10.400 --> 01:00:14.000
[Amit Varma]: are radically networked societies are products of the information age.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:18.160
[Guest]: Exactly. So, there's a fundamental mismatch, right? So, states realize that. Now, what

01:00:18.160 --> 01:00:23.200
[Guest]: will be the state's reaction when they realize that, you know, things are happening too fast

01:00:23.200 --> 01:00:28.680
[Guest]: for us, it's getting out of hand. What states do what they do best, that is excessive use

01:00:28.680 --> 01:00:35.600
[Guest]: of force is one response that we see across these protests, right? Whether in Chile or

01:00:35.600 --> 01:00:40.680
[Guest]: in Lebanon and even in India now, right? So, you will see the excessive use of force for

01:00:40.680 --> 01:00:48.200
[Guest]: this mismatch. So, the state will use law and order machinery to attack the protesters

01:00:48.200 --> 01:00:53.240
[Guest]: and say that that is the only way we were left to clamp down these protests, okay? So, that

01:00:53.240 --> 01:00:56.400
[Guest]: is one sort of response that comes up.

01:00:56.400 --> 01:01:02.200
[Guest]: The second kind of response is, let's take the other extreme. What is a more enlightened

01:01:02.200 --> 01:01:08.400
[Guest]: type of response that you would want the state to have? One way would be for the government

01:01:08.400 --> 01:01:14.280
[Guest]: to have better emergency communication systems to at least refute misinformation which might

01:01:14.280 --> 01:01:19.520
[Guest]: have happened, right? So, for example, I have an example of this. So, a few years back,

01:01:19.520 --> 01:01:25.720
[Guest]: there was a bomb at Church Street, you know, which went off and the rumors started spreading

01:01:25.720 --> 01:01:31.520
[Guest]: on that also very quickly about first it was bomb on Church Street, then the next tweets

01:01:31.520 --> 01:01:36.640
[Guest]: came started coming that bomb near a church. And then third, there were also tweets a bomb

01:01:36.640 --> 01:01:42.120
[Guest]: in a church. I mean, completely untrue, but this misinformation was trying to take it

01:01:42.120 --> 01:01:46.920
[Guest]: in a certain direction, probably make it a communal thing of sort, right? But it was

01:01:46.920 --> 01:01:51.920
[Guest]: quickly clamped down because you had a very credible presence of the Bangalore police

01:01:51.920 --> 01:01:56.960
[Guest]: online, not just Bangalore police, but the commissioner of police had a very visible

01:01:56.960 --> 01:02:03.560
[Guest]: presence and a reputation on that platform that he'd built over time. So, he was quickly

01:02:03.560 --> 01:02:07.720
[Guest]: able to come into the picture and say, hey, that's not wrong. It has happened at such

01:02:07.720 --> 01:02:13.400
[Guest]: and such place, we are looking at the incident and trying to take note of it, right? So,

01:02:13.400 --> 01:02:21.120
[Guest]: that actually ended some of these speculations and which might have led to, you know, more

01:02:21.120 --> 01:02:28.620
[Guest]: nastier things from happening. So, if the governments are also embedded in these networks,

01:02:28.620 --> 01:02:34.280
[Guest]: they understand it better and they have emergency communication systems in place on how to tackle

01:02:34.280 --> 01:02:39.360
[Guest]: these. We might have a more liberal response, at least to one aspect of it, which is misinformation.

01:02:39.360 --> 01:02:46.160
[Guest]: Okay. So, that's the second way to deal with it. Okay. Third part of it is increased surveillance

01:02:46.160 --> 01:02:50.720
[Guest]: is what many states are moving towards. So, they are saying that the only way to do this

01:02:50.720 --> 01:02:58.280
[Guest]: is we need to have control over the encryption keys that WhatsApp users or other platforms

01:02:58.280 --> 01:03:03.400
[Guest]: use in order to get control of this. Again, quite illiberal response, but this is what

01:03:03.400 --> 01:03:08.320
[Guest]: the states are looking at. The fourth one is where governments are saying we will put

01:03:08.320 --> 01:03:12.320
[Guest]: constraints even before this type of information is shared. And that is what you have this

01:03:12.320 --> 01:03:17.620
[Guest]: 66A of the IT Act kind of response, where the government is saying, if you share any

01:03:17.620 --> 01:03:23.920
[Guest]: information which is broadly defined as offensive or of menacing character, we will have some

01:03:23.920 --> 01:03:31.520
[Guest]: penalties, etc. You might be put in jail and all that. So, this is another kind of illiberal

01:03:31.520 --> 01:03:39.800
[Guest]: response which exists. So, now what you see overall is the state realizes or sees or perceives

01:03:39.800 --> 01:03:47.320
[Guest]: this as a fundamental threat to them. And they are being responding with largely illiberal

01:03:47.320 --> 01:03:54.800
[Guest]: responses, which exists as either preconditions on what can be shared, or you have increased

01:03:54.800 --> 01:03:59.880
[Guest]: surveillance, or you have increased use of force. All three quite negative. And on the

01:03:59.880 --> 01:04:04.760
[Guest]: other hand, you have a more liberal response of having better emergency communication systems.

01:04:04.760 --> 01:04:09.280
[Guest]: And largely, states are still opting for the illiberal responses across the world. And

01:04:09.280 --> 01:04:13.280
[Guest]: we are moving towards that. Even in India, the narrative is now, the fact that we see

01:04:13.280 --> 01:04:19.560
[Guest]: WhatsApp enabling this is a very easy excuse for the state to actually say, yeah, the problem

01:04:19.560 --> 01:04:24.800
[Guest]: is not us, the problem is actually WhatsApp. So, give us the encryption keys, we will be

01:04:24.800 --> 01:04:26.360
[Guest]: able to regulate this better.

01:04:26.360 --> 01:04:30.280
[Amit Varma]: No, and also states have a monopoly on violence, which they are used to. So, the instinctive

01:04:30.280 --> 01:04:36.480
[Amit Varma]: response is to react with a sort of violence. And like you, I feel the only one of these

01:04:36.480 --> 01:04:40.280
[Amit Varma]: four responses which you laid out, which I completely agree with and is the right response

01:04:40.280 --> 01:04:44.920
[Amit Varma]: is that the government itself establish a credible presence across networks, so it can

01:04:44.920 --> 01:04:50.760
[Amit Varma]: stop misinformation from spreading. There's a larger question here. And the larger debate

01:04:50.760 --> 01:04:56.360
[Amit Varma]: here, which you've written about for years as well, is the tussle between say, liberty

01:04:56.360 --> 01:05:01.160
[Amit Varma]: and security. And to sort of give a little bit of very quick context for the listeners

01:05:01.160 --> 01:05:06.600
[Amit Varma]: on why this is an age old tussle, or at least a tussle since enlightenment value shaped

01:05:06.600 --> 01:05:12.280
[Amit Varma]: the state is that the whole purpose of the state as liberals like me and Pranay would

01:05:12.280 --> 01:05:18.320
[Amit Varma]: view it is to defend our individual rights. But there is a trade off here that if we want

01:05:18.320 --> 01:05:23.160
[Amit Varma]: our freedoms to be safeguarded by the state, we have to give away some rights to enable

01:05:23.160 --> 01:05:28.120
[Amit Varma]: the state to do this. So, we give the state the right to have a monopoly on violence.

01:05:28.120 --> 01:05:32.840
[Amit Varma]: And of course, the existence of the state is based on our taxes. So, you know, we accept

01:05:32.840 --> 01:05:38.040
[Amit Varma]: that there will be some coercion and therefore some infringement on our rights on our liberties

01:05:38.040 --> 01:05:45.400
[Amit Varma]: for the state to exist. So, we give away a little bit of our liberty for the amount of

01:05:45.400 --> 01:05:51.520
[Amit Varma]: security that we want. And this equation is different across the world. Like you've pointed

01:05:51.520 --> 01:05:56.040
[Amit Varma]: out in your paper in the US, they might give away 10% of liberty for whatever and in other

01:05:56.040 --> 01:06:00.680
[Amit Varma]: places you give away far more liberty like in North Korea, for example. And this is a

01:06:00.680 --> 01:06:05.600
[Amit Varma]: tussle that also comes up in the context of radically networked societies, because many

01:06:05.600 --> 01:06:10.760
[Amit Varma]: of these measures that you spoke about, like the surveillance state, there is no state

01:06:10.760 --> 01:06:15.760
[Amit Varma]: capacity to actually surveil everyone, but like the surveillance state or like just getting

01:06:15.760 --> 01:06:22.640
[Amit Varma]: into a protest and beating up protesters and so on, you know, go towards the side of infringing

01:06:22.640 --> 01:06:28.920
[Amit Varma]: liberties too much for protecting and imagined security. So, how has thinking on this evolved

01:06:28.920 --> 01:06:34.120
[Guest]: in this context? Yeah. So, I think there are some positive

01:06:34.120 --> 01:06:39.240
[Guest]: things to it. So, this is a liberty security trade-off that we spoke about, right? What

01:06:39.240 --> 01:06:43.960
[Guest]: percentage of rights that you give to the state in order to experience security and

01:06:43.960 --> 01:06:50.360
[Guest]: that trade-off varies across different nation states. Now, what you would see in the past

01:06:50.360 --> 01:06:58.200
[Guest]: is when this RNS emerged first, the immediate response was taking the argument of in favor

01:06:58.200 --> 01:07:04.320
[Guest]: of security just prevents liberty and all sorts. So, the classic response was stop the

01:07:04.320 --> 01:07:10.000
[Guest]: internet and India is the internet shutdown capital, right? So, that is one more response

01:07:10.000 --> 01:07:12.680
[Guest]: that they have used. Which doesn't work as you pointed out.

01:07:12.680 --> 01:07:18.520
[Guest]: Yeah, it doesn't work because these networks are very resilient. So, even after you break

01:07:18.520 --> 01:07:22.400
[Guest]: down the internet, there will be other ways that people, once that identity and cause

01:07:22.400 --> 01:07:27.560
[Guest]: has been established, people will find other means to it, right? Like in Hong Kong's case,

01:07:27.560 --> 01:07:32.760
[Guest]: people use Bluetooth file sharing or AirDrop to share documents. In other places, people

01:07:32.760 --> 01:07:39.720
[Guest]: can use satellite phones or other ways to basically keep the network going on. So, that

01:07:39.720 --> 01:07:44.960
[Guest]: was what the state started with, that response of shutting down the internet. But now states

01:07:44.960 --> 01:07:50.200
[Guest]: realize, at least some of them, that maybe that is not the way to go forward and that's

01:07:50.200 --> 01:07:56.000
[Guest]: where they are exploring other means, either in terms of, let's say, surveillance, which

01:07:56.000 --> 01:08:01.440
[Guest]: is problematic for us, but states are exploring that, and the emergency communication system

01:08:01.440 --> 01:08:08.360
[Guest]: as well. So, these are what states are realizing. But again, it varies across states. So, in

01:08:08.360 --> 01:08:13.000
[Guest]: India, I think we would still say we are in the midst of this policy debate where all

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:18.760
[Guest]: these options are currently open, right? Internet is still being closed down in many places.

01:08:18.760 --> 01:08:24.480
[Guest]: Even as we speak in Kashmir, it is still down and the state is also exploring this NAT grid

01:08:24.480 --> 01:08:28.080
[Guest]: that has been there for a long time, that we should have a national grid. There have

01:08:28.080 --> 01:08:33.400
[Guest]: been talks about your WhatsApp login should be linked to your Aadhaar kind of things as

01:08:33.400 --> 01:08:39.000
[Guest]: well, right? So, all this, we are in the midst of that policy debate and it will be interesting

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:41.040
[Guest]: to see where it actually takes us.

01:08:41.040 --> 01:08:46.480
[Amit Varma]: No, and also my question to you is, around what axis does one think about this in terms

01:08:46.480 --> 01:08:52.720
[Amit Varma]: of instrumentality or morality? For example, you know, Sunil Abraham pointed out that there's

01:08:52.720 --> 01:08:57.760
[Amit Varma]: a false dichotomy between privacy and security. And I'll quote him where he says, quote, an

01:08:57.760 --> 01:09:03.040
[Amit Varma]: optimization approach to resolving the false dichotomy between privacy and security will

01:09:03.040 --> 01:09:07.520
[Amit Varma]: not allow for a total surveillance regime as pursued by the US administration, stop

01:09:07.520 --> 01:09:12.240
[Amit Varma]: quote. And his point is that there is like a hockey stick curve, that there is a point

01:09:12.240 --> 01:09:16.840
[Amit Varma]: at which is optimal, where you take away some liberties, but you provide a certain amount

01:09:16.840 --> 01:09:21.720
[Amit Varma]: of security. And that's where you should stop. The analogy he uses is like salt in cooking,

01:09:21.720 --> 01:09:26.200
[Amit Varma]: that you know, food without salt is tasteless. But beyond the point, if you put too much

01:09:26.200 --> 01:09:30.760
[Amit Varma]: salt, it is also tasteless. So, you have to get the amount right. And this is an approach

01:09:30.760 --> 01:09:35.680
[Amit Varma]: which would look at it in instrumental terms, that we are trying to provide this much security

01:09:35.680 --> 01:09:40.680
[Amit Varma]: and therefore, we take away this many liberties and it becomes almost an engineering problem,

01:09:40.680 --> 01:09:45.520
[Amit Varma]: as it were. But the other approach would be to also take into account the moral aspect

01:09:45.520 --> 01:09:49.840
[Amit Varma]: of it and say that, no, I don't care what the instrumentalities are. Beyond the point,

01:09:49.840 --> 01:09:51.240
[Amit Varma]: you cannot take away my liberties.

01:09:51.240 --> 01:09:56.520
[Guest]: Yeah, I think, I think both of us fall on the other side of the moral argument, right?

01:09:56.520 --> 01:10:03.840
[Guest]: You would want the state to have as little a role in restricting liberties, as it already

01:10:03.840 --> 01:10:09.320
[Guest]: restricts our liberties in many, many areas. Yeah, so you don't want another additional

01:10:09.320 --> 01:10:16.280
[Guest]: tool in the hands of the state. So, we are wary of that. And that's why there are other

01:10:16.280 --> 01:10:21.320
[Guest]: responses, right? But the thing is, you need to have state capacity to be able to execute

01:10:21.320 --> 01:10:27.240
[Guest]: any of those, right? Let's say you want excellent emergency communication systems or ways for

01:10:27.240 --> 01:10:34.360
[Guest]: states. Let's say, if there is actually a real case of a riot happening because of these

01:10:34.360 --> 01:10:41.560
[Guest]: information systems, it is reported. Can states probably consider, in a very localized way,

01:10:41.560 --> 01:10:47.320
[Guest]: probably slowing down the scale of this spreading of this information, either through appearance

01:10:47.320 --> 01:10:52.720
[Guest]: of credible information on WhatsApp, or even say, let's say, considering slowing down the

01:10:52.720 --> 01:10:57.800
[Guest]: internet in a very localized area. Again, it is, there is a problem of illiberal thing

01:10:57.800 --> 01:11:03.440
[Guest]: that we are approaching. But as a moral point, you don't want, definitely, internet shutdowns

01:11:03.440 --> 01:11:08.680
[Guest]: are not the way to go, right? It is a severe restriction of liberty of a large number of

01:11:08.680 --> 01:11:14.640
[Guest]: people in the name of security. And because of a few rioters, you are going to affect

01:11:14.640 --> 01:11:18.440
[Guest]: a lot of other people as well. Or many of these responses, actually, which we talked

01:11:18.440 --> 01:11:26.320
[Guest]: about, are, violate that moral stand that we come from, right? And, yeah.

01:11:26.320 --> 01:11:30.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And I mean, I'm just thinking of the counter arguments. For example, I'm against

01:11:30.840 --> 01:11:36.040
[Amit Varma]: torture. But one counter thought experiment that is often made up, which is often presented

01:11:36.040 --> 01:11:40.400
[Amit Varma]: to me by people arguing the other side, is that what if there's a nuclear bomb in the

01:11:40.400 --> 01:11:43.800
[Amit Varma]: middle of Bombay, and you know, it's about to go off and one person has a code and you

01:11:43.800 --> 01:11:48.160
[Amit Varma]: know, he has a code, but he's not giving it away, should you torture him? And that, you

01:11:48.160 --> 01:11:52.160
[Amit Varma]: know, it's again instrumentality versus morality, but then it seems a no brainer that you have

01:11:52.160 --> 01:11:56.920
[Amit Varma]: to save the lives of so many people. So what do you do? And a similar argument could be,

01:11:56.920 --> 01:11:59.960
[Amit Varma]: the government has made similar arguments. It's not a thought experiment in the case

01:11:59.960 --> 01:12:04.240
[Amit Varma]: of Kashmir by saying that we had to shut down the internet, because terrorists will communicate

01:12:04.240 --> 01:12:10.800
[Amit Varma]: with each other. And this, of course, is a rubbish argument. But this is a sort of argument

01:12:10.800 --> 01:12:16.040
[Amit Varma]: which people are making, where the state also can say that, listen, I accept that the only

01:12:16.040 --> 01:12:20.480
[Amit Varma]: job of the state, I'll concede your libertarian point that the only job of the state is to

01:12:20.480 --> 01:12:25.760
[Amit Varma]: safeguard you and safeguard your rights, but I need to do this for that. How do such arguments

01:12:25.760 --> 01:12:29.280
[Amit Varma]: play out? How have they played out in India in the policy space?

01:12:29.280 --> 01:12:37.280
[Guest]: In the Indian case, I think we already have, there are not many qualms about the state

01:12:37.280 --> 01:12:43.840
[Guest]: acquiring more power, unfortunately. So the state has been able to clamp down on freedoms

01:12:43.840 --> 01:12:46.560
[Amit Varma]: more easily. And it's normalized. Most of India doesn't

01:12:46.560 --> 01:12:49.640
[Amit Varma]: give a shit that Kashmir hasn't had internet for almost six months.

01:12:49.640 --> 01:12:56.920
[Guest]: Yeah. So that's what the Indian case has been, unfortunately. And that liberty argument which

01:12:56.920 --> 01:13:03.640
[Guest]: we are making is not the one which is very popular currently, right? So, yeah, that's

01:13:03.640 --> 01:13:04.640
[Amit Varma]: where we are.

01:13:04.640 --> 01:13:09.240
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, before we go, I'm, you know, just thinking back for a moment beyond radically

01:13:09.240 --> 01:13:15.280
[Amit Varma]: network societies into radical networking, per se, like, just as a lot of these liberal

01:13:15.280 --> 01:13:20.280
[Amit Varma]: movements have been enabled by technology. I mean, I often say that, even as states grow

01:13:20.280 --> 01:13:25.560
[Amit Varma]: stronger and stronger, the best libertarian hope is that technology will empower individuals,

01:13:25.560 --> 01:13:29.240
[Amit Varma]: which also seems to be happening. But it's equally true if you look at it another way

01:13:29.240 --> 01:13:33.200
[Amit Varma]: that a lot of these right-wing populist movements that have come up have also been enabled by

01:13:33.200 --> 01:13:37.160
[Amit Varma]: technology in the sense, and this is something I've written about, and we've spoken about

01:13:37.160 --> 01:13:43.680
[Amit Varma]: in the past on how, what social media perhaps did was that it created preference cascades

01:13:43.680 --> 01:13:47.560
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that, and these are the words of Timur Koran, he talks about how people

01:13:47.560 --> 01:13:51.360
[Amit Varma]: typically carry out preference falsification, that they don't express what they really feel

01:13:51.360 --> 01:13:56.840
[Amit Varma]: about something because they're not sure if there are others like them. For example, Soviet

01:13:56.840 --> 01:14:01.320
[Amit Varma]: dissidents under the Soviet Union who did not know that if they felt anger at the regime,

01:14:01.320 --> 01:14:04.080
[Amit Varma]: they would not say it because they didn't know there were others like them. But then

01:14:04.080 --> 01:14:08.160
[Amit Varma]: a moment comes when you realize that everybody shares, there are enough people and you have

01:14:08.160 --> 01:14:13.040
[Amit Varma]: what is called a preference cascade. And Glenn Reynolds, a kind stuff under the old school

01:14:13.040 --> 01:14:18.520
[Amit Varma]: blogger once wrote a piece about how Trump's rise, according to him, was enabled by preference

01:14:18.520 --> 01:14:24.240
[Amit Varma]: cascades because suddenly a lot of people realized that the thoughts that they were

01:14:24.240 --> 01:14:28.440
[Amit Varma]: otherwise wary of expressing because it didn't seem politically correct, were actually shared

01:14:28.440 --> 01:14:33.760
[Amit Varma]: by a lot of people. And this coming together of silent majorities, you know, enabled Trump

01:14:33.760 --> 01:14:38.840
[Amit Varma]: to come to power. And in a similar sense, it could be argued that the rise of Modi to

01:14:38.840 --> 01:14:46.440
[Amit Varma]: some extent was enabled by this, where a lot of people, you know, in some cases, perhaps,

01:14:46.440 --> 01:14:50.640
[Amit Varma]: where a lot of people suddenly realized that everybody shares, whatever it is that draws

01:14:50.640 --> 01:14:55.240
[Amit Varma]: them to Modi's vision of India, maybe the desire for a Hindu Rashtra or a hatred of

01:14:55.240 --> 01:14:59.160
[Amit Varma]: Muslims or bigotry or sexism or whatever. And I'm sure there are positive things also,

01:14:59.160 --> 01:15:04.400
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to indicate that everybody who voted or votes for Modi is necessarily falls

01:15:04.400 --> 01:15:08.880
[Amit Varma]: into one of these categories. Though at the moment, I can't imagine too many positive

01:15:08.880 --> 01:15:13.200
[Amit Varma]: categories of voting for him. And all of this has also been enabled by social media. So

01:15:13.200 --> 01:15:19.240
[Amit Varma]: there are these countervailing things, processes sort of happening within society. And at the

01:15:19.240 --> 01:15:23.960
[Amit Varma]: same time, the coercive power of the state has also been enabled by technology, like

01:15:23.960 --> 01:15:30.000
[Amit Varma]: I retweeted something someone pointed out a few days ago, about how a lot of people

01:15:30.000 --> 01:15:34.320
[Amit Varma]: who were near a protest somewhere in Kerala, I think, were got noticed, got show cause

01:15:34.320 --> 01:15:37.680
[Amit Varma]: notices from the government that what were you doing there? And how did the government

01:15:37.680 --> 01:15:42.640
[Amit Varma]: know they were there because their cell phone signals are picked up by the cell phone tower,

01:15:42.640 --> 01:15:47.000
[Amit Varma]: something of that sort. And the government, of course, has like incredibly scary surveillance

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:51.720
[Amit Varma]: technologies, that they might even be listening to this podcast at the time of recording and

01:15:51.720 --> 01:15:58.360
[Amit Varma]: not at the time of release. Hello, bureaucrat, if you're listening. So looking ahead into

01:15:58.360 --> 01:16:03.400
[Amit Varma]: the future, where technology is both a cause for hope and despair, what is sort of a worst

01:16:03.400 --> 01:16:07.840
[Amit Varma]: case scenario 10 years down the line and a best case scenario 10 years down the line?

01:16:07.840 --> 01:16:16.080
[Guest]: So, the best case scenario, I would say would be where these imagined communities which

01:16:16.080 --> 01:16:21.200
[Guest]: are there, might be they are able to create new communities, new imagined identities,

01:16:21.200 --> 01:16:28.080
[Guest]: which didn't exist earlier, on the lines which sort of are more humane towards each other,

01:16:28.080 --> 01:16:34.000
[Guest]: which see each other as an individual rather than as a part of a specific background, right?

01:16:34.000 --> 01:16:41.160
[Guest]: So, their caste, colour, religion, but just seeing it as we are all humans. So, just because

01:16:41.160 --> 01:16:45.400
[Guest]: of that, we need to move more sympathetic to each other. If that happens, and we are

01:16:45.400 --> 01:16:51.120
[Guest]: able to form new imagined identities on those lines, maybe the world will move towards the

01:16:51.120 --> 01:16:56.800
[Guest]: world. It's a very philosophical thing, but I don't have a concrete answer to say. The

01:16:56.800 --> 01:17:02.680
[Guest]: second one on that would be the negative part would be, yeah, these identities actually

01:17:02.680 --> 01:17:08.360
[Guest]: reaffirm our existing biases. And there are new RNSs which happened on already existing

01:17:08.360 --> 01:17:14.640
[Guest]: caste, class lines. So, that again leads to a lot of problems. Look at the cause angle,

01:17:14.640 --> 01:17:19.880
[Guest]: you know, and as we discussed about how consumer protests are being taken, a negative scenario

01:17:19.880 --> 01:17:25.480
[Guest]: also is maybe now increasing prices of anything or decreasing subsidies of anything will become

01:17:25.480 --> 01:17:31.000
[Guest]: difficult, because there might be radically network mobilizations in opposition to these.

01:17:31.000 --> 01:17:37.320
[Amit Varma]: In fact, TikTok for a while had like 356 million views for some hashtag which had onions in

01:17:37.320 --> 01:17:43.040
[Amit Varma]: it, which and there were 1000s of videos protesting the price rise of onions, which was radically

01:17:43.040 --> 01:17:46.320
[Amit Varma]: networked entertainment, but not exactly a movement.

01:17:46.320 --> 01:17:50.840
[Guest]: Yeah, and so that's a problem, right? So, because you already have these strong endowment

01:17:50.840 --> 01:17:56.200
[Guest]: effects, especially in India on everything, right? We get so much tax benefit. So, we

01:17:56.200 --> 01:18:01.640
[Guest]: are that endowment effect is there. And if the government wants to end these, imagine

01:18:01.640 --> 01:18:06.360
[Guest]: there is a radically network mobilization, which takes this as an immediate cause the

01:18:06.360 --> 01:18:13.400
[Guest]: identity aspect might be built in over years, but it will become even more difficult for

01:18:13.400 --> 01:18:18.160
[Guest]: these subsidies to be taken out as well. So, that's a sort of a negative scenario.

01:18:18.160 --> 01:18:22.240
[Amit Varma]: And I guess it might be an element of populism as well. For example, one legitimate cause

01:18:22.240 --> 01:18:26.520
[Amit Varma]: which everyone should protest is a rising unemployment in India and the jobs crisis.

01:18:26.520 --> 01:18:31.880
[Amit Varma]: But one unproductive way of protesting it is when groups like the party that's for example,

01:18:31.880 --> 01:18:35.920
[Amit Varma]: come together and just ask for more government reservations for themselves, which does nothing

01:18:35.920 --> 01:18:40.880
[Amit Varma]: to solve the structural reasons for the problem. But, you know, the structural reasons of the

01:18:40.880 --> 01:18:46.160
[Amit Varma]: problem are so sort of abstract and counterintuitive that they're not going to get you're not going

01:18:46.160 --> 01:18:50.880
[Amit Varma]: to mobilize masses around those things. So, you have the right cause, but a movement that

01:18:50.880 --> 01:18:56.440
[Amit Varma]: demands perhaps the wrong action or action which doesn't really solve the problem. And

01:18:56.440 --> 01:19:00.680
[Amit Varma]: you can have more localized RNSs around these.

01:19:00.680 --> 01:19:06.720
[Guest]: One more, we can look at sort of a negative aspect of it is the look at the role of the

01:19:06.720 --> 01:19:11.360
[Guest]: elected representative, that also fundamentally changes in the sense that, you know, there

01:19:11.360 --> 01:19:16.600
[Guest]: has been an age old debate about what is the role of the elected representative? Is he

01:19:16.600 --> 01:19:22.920
[Guest]: an ambassador for whatever the constituents think or he or she can apply their mind to

01:19:22.920 --> 01:19:28.600
[Guest]: a particular policy problem, right? There's Edmund Burke's famous speech to the electors

01:19:28.600 --> 01:19:34.360
[Guest]: of Bristol. It talks about all these, right? So now imagine how will that play out when

01:19:34.360 --> 01:19:40.760
[Guest]: everyone is radically networked. It becomes difficult for a person to take a position

01:19:40.760 --> 01:19:47.360
[Guest]: against the stream of opinion which already exists. So imagine already, people have hardened

01:19:47.360 --> 01:19:52.760
[Guest]: their opinions and stance through a radically networked community mobilized on that. Will

01:19:52.760 --> 01:19:59.440
[Guest]: that representative can they afford to take a position against this becomes slightly difficult.

01:19:59.440 --> 01:20:03.400
[Amit Varma]: And it also might lead to something of a status quo bias in the sense you're scared of doing

01:20:03.400 --> 01:20:08.720
[Amit Varma]: anything at all. Because doing anything at all raises a risk for you from a radically

01:20:08.720 --> 01:20:13.840
[Amit Varma]: networked and very polarized populace. So you just try to sort of stay invisible and

01:20:13.840 --> 01:20:14.840
[Guest]: stay out of trouble.

01:20:14.840 --> 01:20:21.000
[Guest]: Let's end on a positive note. There might be some imagined identities which are formed

01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:28.200
[Guest]: across the barriers of our nation state across the barriers of our immediate communities,

01:20:28.200 --> 01:20:33.920
[Guest]: right, which are there. So therein lies the hope that these new communities will be able

01:20:33.920 --> 01:20:39.520
[Guest]: to transcend some of the already existing fault lines. And they will push the agenda

01:20:39.520 --> 01:20:45.400
[Guest]: of the government in a direction which is beneficial for both sides across that.

01:20:45.400 --> 01:20:48.600
[Amit Varma]: And who knows this community could be listeners of the seen and the unseen. We can call them

01:20:48.600 --> 01:20:53.480
[Amit Varma]: unseeners. Pranay, thank you so much for coming on the show again.

01:20:53.480 --> 01:20:54.880
[Amit Varma]: Thanks, Amit.

